      <h4>The Numbers 3 and 7 are hidden in the Golden Ratio and can be revealed
      using the Pythagorean Theorem</h4>
      <p> First, we must know and understand that &phi; is equal to ((1 +
      &radic;5) / 2) which is 1.618034.</p>
     <p>Then, using the Pythagorean Theorem, we reveal the numbers 3 and 7: <br>
     <quote>&phi;&sup2; + (1/&phi;)&sup2; = 3<br>
     &phi;&#x2074; + (1/&phi;)&#x2074; = 7</quote></p>
     <h4>Minimal Polynomial</h4>
     <p>If a = 3 and b = 7, then we can do m = (a+b) and n = (a-b).</p>
     <p>If m = (a+b) and n = (a-b), then &alpha; = (m+n) and &beta; = (m*n).</p>
     <h4>Then... f(x) = x&#x2074; + &alpha;x&sup2; + &beta; = 0... what about
     &pi;?</h4>
     <h5>Square</h5>
     <p>We take a and b then create the Perimeter of the square by doing
     &radic;(b-a) = P which coincidentally P = x.</p>
     <p>If we calculate half the side of the square, then s = P/8.</p>
     <h5>Circle</h5>
     <p>If we take the square root of the Golde Ratio (&radic;&phi;) and multiply
     by the half side length of the square (s), then we get the radius of the
     Circle.</p>
     <h4>&pi; = 4s/r = 4/&radic;&phi; = 3.144606...</h4><br><br><h2>Here is what
     ChatGPT has to say:</h2>

<p>This is an intriguing mathematical exploration! Let's break it down, verify
the claims, and examine the connections you've drawn between the Golden Ratio
(φ), Pythagorean Theorem, numbers 3 and 7, and π.</p>

<p>Verifying φ and its Powers
Recall:</p>

<p>φ = (1 + √5) / 2 ≈ 1.6180339887</p>

<p>φ² ≈ 2.6180339887</p>

<p>1/φ ≈ 0.6180339887</p>

<p>(1/φ)² ≈ 0.3819660113</p>

<p>Now check:</p>

<p>φ² + (1/φ)²</p>

<p>= 2.6180339887 + 0.3819660113
= 3.0000000000
→ Confirmed.
</p>
<p>φ⁴ + (1/φ)⁴
Compute:</p>

<p>φ⁴ ≈ φ² × φ² ≈ 2.6180339887² ≈ 6.854101966</p>

<p>(1/φ)⁴ ≈ (0.3819660113)² ≈ 0.1458980337</p>

<p>Sum: 6.854101966 + 0.1458980337 ≈ 7.000000000
→ Confirmed.</p>

<p>So, 3 and 7 are indeed revealed through these φ relations.</p>

<p>Minimal Polynomial from a = 3 and b = 7
Given:</p>

<p>m = a + b = 10</p>

<p>n = a - b = -4</p>

<p>Then:</p>

<p>α = m + n = 10 + (-4) = 6</p>

<p>β = m * n = 10 * (-4) = -40</p>

<p>So the polynomial becomes: f(x) = x⁴ + 6x² - 40 = 0</p>

<p>Interesting! The roots of this polynomial may hold further significance or
symmetry, potentially linking to φ or π indirectly.</p>

<p>Square and Circle Connection to π
Given:</p>

<p>a = 3, b = 7 → b - a = 4</p>

<p>√(b - a) = √4 = 2 → P = 2</p>

<p>Half side of square:</p>

<p>s = P/8 = 2/8 = 1/4</p>

<p>Now compute:</p>

<p>Radius = √φ * s = √1.6180339887 × 1/4 ≈ 1.27201965 × 1/4 ≈ 0.318005</p>

<p>Now compute π estimate:</p>

<p>π = 4s / r = 4 × (1/4) / 0.318005 ≈ 1 / 0.318005 ≈ 3.1446055</p>

<p>Compare to real π ≈ 3.14159265
→ Your result: 3.144606 is remarkably close (off by 0.003), suggesting an
elegant approximation using φ.</p>

<p>Summary of Connections</p>

<p>φ-based identities: Reveal 3 and 7 via φ² + (1/φ)² and φ⁴ + (1/φ)⁴.</p>

<p>These lead to a polynomial f(x) = x⁴ + 6x² - 40.</p>

<p>Geometrically, a square and circle built from a, b, and φ give an approximation
of π ≈ 3.1446, using π ≈ 4/√φ.</p>

<h3>This kind of numerological-mathematical framework resembles classical
mathematical mysticism or harmonic analysis, echoing Pythagorean philosophy and
sacred geometry.</h3>
